Disks can be turned into a slower Random Access Memory (RAM) through the use of memory-mapped files. Memory-mapped files allow a portion of a file or an entire file to be mapped into the memory space of a process. This process enables applications to access files on disk in the same way they access dynamic memory, through pointers, which can simplify coding and increase performance for certain applications, especially those requiring manipulation of large files. The concept doesn't exactly transform the disk into RAM, but it allows file I/O to be treated as memory access, thus blurring the line between disk access and memory access from the programmer's perspective.

The required system call for creating a memory-mapped file in Unix-like systems (Linux, macOS, etc.) is `mmap()`. The corresponding system call in Windows is `CreateFileMapping()` combined with `MapViewOfFile()`.

Here's a Linux example, in C, using `mmap()` to map a file into memory, modify a part of it as if it were an array in memory, and then clean up:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/mman.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/stat.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <string.h>

int main()
{
    // The file we'll map
    const char* filepath = "example.dat";

    // Open the file
    int fd = open(filepath, O_RDWR);
    if (fd == -1) {
        perror("Error opening file for writing");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    // Get the size of the file
    struct stat st;
    if (fstat(fd, &st) == -1) {
        perror("Error getting the file size");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }
    size_t filesize = st.st_size;

    // Execute mmap
    char* map = mmap(0, filesize, PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE, MAP_SHARED, fd, 0);
    if (map == MAP_FAILED) {
        close(fd);
        perror("Error mmapping the file");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    // Now the file is mapped in the memory. Let's modify a part of it as an example.
    // Be very careful with the offset and data size to avoid segmentation faults.
    // For example, change the first byte
    map[0] = 'J';

    // Writing back isn't necessary as changes are directly made in the memory-mapped area
    // However, you need to sync the memory with the file.
    if (msync(map, filesize, MS_SYNC) == -1) {
        perror("Could not sync the file with memory");
    }

    // Unmap and close
    if (munmap(map, filesize) == -1) {
        close(fd);
        perror("Error un-mmapping the file");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    close(fd);
    return 0;
}
```

This example opens a file, `example.dat`, creates a memory-mapped file, modifies the first byte, syncs the changes, and then cleans up. Note that the file must exist and have a size greater than 0. The size of the mapping and file access mode should match the intended use. Also, for actual use, error checking and more sophisticated handling would be necessary, especially for production-level code.

